{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630978"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.14,0.06,0.03,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78695"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10028"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5325"},{"type":"tags","id":"7231"},{"type":"tags","id":"7337"},{"type":"tags","id":"7357"},{"type":"tags","id":"7374"},{"type":"tags","id":"7398"},{"type":"tags","id":"7399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23484"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78695"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a laceration to his right forearm from broken glass. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his vital signs are within normal limits. There is a 4 cm laceration on the volar aspect of his right forearm, 3 cm proximal to the wrist. Allen\u0027s test reveals poor filling of the palm when the radial artery is released while maintaining ulnar compression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely anatomical finding at surgery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete transection of the superficial branch of the radial nerve","Complete transection of the ulnar artery","Complete transection of the anterior interosseous artery","Partial transection of the median nerve","Complete transection of the radial artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario describes a positive Allen\u0027s test, which assesses the patency of the radial and ulnar arteries in the forearm. The test involves compressing both arteries while the patient makes a fist, then releasing pressure on one artery while maintaining compression of the other. Poor filling when the \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial artery\u003C/strong\u003E is released suggests radial artery disruption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar artery\u003C/strong\u003E is intact in this case, as evidenced by normal palm perfusion when it is released during Allen\u0027s test. The ulnar artery is the dominant contributor to the superficial palmar arch, which provides the main blood supply to the fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial transection of the median nerve\u003C/strong\u003E would present with sensory changes in the lateral three and a half digits and weakness of thumb opposition, which are not described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial branch of the radial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily sensory and supplies the dorsal aspect of the lateral three and a half digits. Its transection would not affect arterial flow to the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior interosseous artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a small branch of the ulnar artery that supplies the deep muscles of the forearm. Its transection would not affect the Allen\u0027s test result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial artery bifurcates at the level of the cubital fossa into the radial and ulnar arteries. These arteries form anastomotic networks in the hand via the superficial and deep palmar arches, providing collateral circulation that can maintain hand perfusion even if one artery is compromised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The brachial artery bifurcates into radial and ulnar arteries at the level of the cubital fossa.","The radial artery is the primary contributor to the deep palmar arch.","The ulnar artery is the primary contributor to the superficial palmar arch.","Allen\u0027s test assesses the patency of radial and ulnar arteries by evaluating palmar perfusion."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017.","Beutel BG, Worley C, Zisquit J, et al. Allen Test. [Updated 2024 Oct 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64038"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T09:27:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T09:29:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10028"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78695"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91",